Description.div: This lesson looks at Knowing Your Customer – AML/CTF Programs.
You should complete the lesson in about 15 minutes. You will learn about:

ul.li: What your obligations are in relation to complying with your organisation's AML/CTF Program

Description.div: To get started, please click on the Next button below.

The risk that a reporting entity (i.e. an organisation providing designated services) may reasonably face that the provision of its designated services might (whether inadvertently or otherwise) involve or facilitate money laundering or the financing of terrorism is known as "ML/TF" risk.
From 12 December 2007, each reporting entity must have an AML/CTF Program, Part A of which must have as its primary purpose, the identification, management and mitigation of its ML/TF risk.
The AML/CTF Act and Rules have been designed so that the content of your organisation's AML/CTF Program can be based, in part, on your organisation's assessment of its ML/TF risk.
In determining ML/TF risk, your organisation must consider the risk posed by the following factors:

ul.li: types of designated services it provides;
methods of delivering its designated services; and
foreign jurisdictions with which it deals.

Description.div: It is your obligation to comply with the requirements and procedures of your organisation's AML/CTF Program to the extent that it is relevant to your role and duties.

Page.Title: AML/CTF Programs and the AML/CTF Act and Rules

Description.div: From the 12 December 2007, every reporting entity must have and comply with an AML/CTF Program.

It is important to remember that you cannot commence to provide a designated service to a customer after the 12 December 2007 if your organisation has not adopted and does not maintain an AML/CTF Program.

Civil Penalties
Providing a designated service to a customer without adopting and maintaining an AML/CTF Program can attract a civil penalty under the AML/CTF Act. Penalties of up to $11 million may be imposed on a company (for example, your organisation), or up to $2.2 million on an individual (i.e. you!).
A reporting entity must have one of the following types of AML/CTF Programs:
For more information about the different types of AML/CTF Programs, see sections 84, 85 and 86 of the AML/CTF Act.

Although, as an employee, you need only comply with the requirements of your organisation's AML/CTF Program to the extent that it is relevant to your role and duties, this module advises on what an AML/CTF Program should address.
An AML/CTF Program must contain two parts – Part A and Part B.

ul.li: Part A must set out systems and controls designed to identify, mitigate and manage the reporting entities ML/TF risk; and
Part B must set out the applicable customer identification procedures to be followed by the reporting entity in identifying its customers.

Page.Title: Content of AML/CTF Program - Part A

Description.div:
There are four main content requirements of Part A of an AML/CTF Program:
1. Changes in risk
It must include procedures to enable your organisation to identify significant changes in ML/TF risk and to assess the risk posed in particular by all new designated services (prior to their introduction), all new methods of delivery of designated services (prior to their adoption), and all new and developing technologies to be used in providing designated services (prior to their adoption).

It must include an AML/CTF risk awareness training program for employees. The training program must be designed to enable employees to understand their organisation's obligations under the AML/CTF Act and Rules, the consequences of non-compliance with the AML/CTF Act and Rules, the type of ML/TF risk the organisation may face and how their organisations AML/CTF Program is relevant to the work carried out by each employee.
This salt™ Program forms part of your organisation's AML/CTF awareness training.
It must include an employee due diligence program which includes appropriate risk-based systems and controls to determine whether to, and, in what manner to:

ul.li: screen any prospective employee whose role may place them in a position to engage in money laundering or terrorist financing; and
re-screen any employee who assumes a role which may place them in a position to engage in money laundering or terrorist financing.

Description.div: It must also establish a system for managing any employee who fails to comply with any procedures established under the AML/CTF Program.

It must provide for your organisation to appoint an AML/CTF Compliance Officer at management level.
Part A of the AML/CTF Program must be approved by and be subject to ongoing oversight by your organisation's board and senior management.
For further information see Chapter 8 of the AML/CTF Rules.

Page.Title: Content of AML/CTF Program – Part B

Description.div: Part B of your AML/CTF Program must set out your organisation's required customer identification procedures. Different customer types attract different levels of ML/TF risk. This means that your organisation's customer identification procedures will differ between different types of the following customers:

Commencing 12 December 2007, the AML/CTF Act prohibits a reporting entity from commencing to provide a designated service to a customer unless it has carried out the "applicable customer identification procedure" in respect of the customer. (This requirement and exceptions to it are discussed further in the Identification lesson. It is a matter for each reporting entity to determine for itself, in accordance with requirements of the AML/CTF Rules and its assessment of AML/CTF risk it faces, what the applicable customer identification (and verification) procedures should be. The reporting entity must then detail its applicable customer identification procedures in Part B of its AML/CTF Program.

The customer identification procedures must outline what customer information your organisation must collect from each customer, what customer information must be verified at a minimum, what is used to verify the information and a procedure for when discrepancies arise.
Your obligation is to comply with these procedures.
For further information about the customer identification procedures required to be addressed by Part B of an AML/CTF Program, see Chapter 4 AML/CTF Rules.
